Kaggle Competition: KKBox’s Music Recommendation Challenge

YX.Wang

The music streaming service company KKBOX held two competitions on KAGGLE earlier.One is a regression problem and another is a classification problem.The competition I took (the later one) requires participants to predict the probability of a user listening to a song repetitively after the first observable listening event.

Outline:

  • A quick EDA and data preprocessing.

  • Feature engineering.

  • Training the model.

Package loading, data importing and data merging

In the data preprocessing and data manipulation part,I will use package data.table as my main tool since it’s more efficient when handling large data frame.

First,we need three consecutive left-join operations to construct our main data frame.The primary key is msno (member id) and song_id.

all <- rbind.fill(train,test)

all_members <- members[all,on="msno"]
all_song <- song[all_members,on="song_id"]
all_all <- song_ex[all_song,on="song_id"]

When looking at the features,some very direct conjectures arise: what’s the relation of three seemly informative variables (e.g. source_system_tab, source_screen_name and source_type) and target?

For convenience sake, let’s define the fuction first.The function will count the number of observations in one column’s each class, then make the results visualizable!

target_vs_column <-function(df, col_name, x , y, title)
                  {  
                  temp_df <- df %>% 
                          group_by_(col_name) %>% 
                          summarize(count=n(), mean_target=mean(target)) %>% 
                          arrange(desc(mean_target)) 
                  
                  df_plot <- temp_df %>%  
                            ggplot(aes_string(col_name,"mean_target")) + 
                            geom_col(aes(fill=count)) +
                            scale_fill_gradient(low='lightskyblue', high='pink2')+
                            coord_flip() +
                            labs(x=x,
                                 y=y,
                                 title=title)
                          
                  print(df_plot)
                  return (temp_df)                 
}

The information that contribute by these three features seems consistent: users will replay the songs they really love and hence tend to restore these enchanting songs in their local library.

The next nature question are: Can the popular songs attract users to replay more times? and Are the frequent users more likely to repeat songs?

Song popularity v.s. Target

target_vs_colcount <- function(df, col_name, x, y, title)
                    { 
                    df %>% 
                      group_by_(col_name) %>% 
                      summarize(count=n(), mean_target=mean(target)) %>% 
                      group_by(count) %>% 
                      summarize(new_count=n(), avg_target=mean(mean_target)) %>% 
                      rename(no_of_songs=new_count, occurence=count) %>% 
                      print %>% 
                      arrange(desc(avg_target)) %>% 
                      print %>% 
                      ggplot(aes(occurence, avg_target)) +
                      geom_point(color='peachpuff2') +
                      geom_smooth(color='firebrick1') +
                      labs(x=x,
                           y=y,
                           title=title)
}

The occurance means frequency of occurrence of a song.In brief, you can regard occurance as the popularity of the song and the no_of_songs as the number of songs that correponds to that occurance.

Members’ characteristic

members_colgroup <- function(df,col_name, x, y, title,xmin,xmax)
                    {                     
                    temp_df <- df %>% 
                                  group_by_(col_name) %>% 
                                  count() %>% 
                                  arrange(desc(n))
                    
                    df_plot <- temp_df %>% 
                                    ggplot(aes_string(col_name, "n")) + 
                                    geom_col(fill='firebrick1') + 
                                    labs(x=x,
                                         y=y,
                                         title=title)+
                                    xlim(xmin, xmax)
                    
                    print(df_plot)
                    return(temp_df)
}

all_all$bd <- ifelse(all_all$bd>80 | all_all$bd<6,NA,all_all$bd)

Feature engineering

We’ll perform feature engineering in the order of songs’ attributes then members’ attributes.

Songs’ attributes

ISRC is the abbreviation of International Standard Recording Code.The first two characters mean Country Code and the sixth to seventh characters represent Year of Reference.

all_all[,":="(record_country=substr(isrc,1,2),
              record_year=ifelse(as.numeric(substr(isrc,6,7))>17,
                            as.numeric(substr(isrc,6,7))+1900,
                            as.numeric(substr(isrc,6,7))+2000),
              name=NULL,
              isrc=NULL)
        ]

Furthermore, there are lots of features about songs were not consistently recorded, hence we can’t parse them perfectly.For example,the artist “姚中仁” is the same person of “MC Hotdog” so there are no systematic way to distinguish the numbers of composers of a song with composer “姚中仁 MC HotDog 陳昱榕 Ｅ-SO 周文傑 KENZY 林睦淵”.We tried to find as many patterns as possible, but again, not perfectly.

all_all[,":="(num_lyr=str_count(lyricist,"\\| | \\/ | \\\\ | \\; | 、")+1,
         num_comp=str_count(composer,"\\| | \\/ | \\\\ | \\; | 、")+1,
         num_art=str_count(artist_name,"\\| | \\/ | \\\\ | \\; | 、")+1,
         is_ft=ifelse(grepl("ft\\.",artist_name) | grepl("feat",artist_name),"feat","non-feat"),
         art_comp_same=ifelse(artist_name==composer,"same","diff"),
         art_lyr_same=ifelse(artist_name==lyricist,"same","diff"),
         art_lyr_comp_same=ifelse(artist_name==lyricist & artist_name==composer & lyricist==composer,"same","diff"),
         long_short=ifelse(song_length>mean(song_length,na.rm=T),"long","short"))
        ]

Members’ attributes

all_all[,":="(reg_year=substr(registration_init_time,1,4),
                reg_month=substr(registration_init_time,5,6),
                reg_day=substr(registration_init_time,7,8),
                exp_year=substr(expiration_date,1,4),
                exp_month=substr(expiration_date,5,6),
                exp_day=substr(expiration_date,7,8),
                duration=as.numeric(ymd(all_all$expiration_date)-ymd(all_all$registration_init_time)))
        ]

Training

Before training models, we would like to mention about the reason why we choose Lightgbm as our tool.

Due to the high cardinality of predictors, one-hot-encoding which another famous GBM counterpart XGBoost requires should not be appropriate.Fortunately, Lightgbm can handle categorical features more theorically.

The next problem of data is the sparsity.Another lately-released GBM package CatBoost doesn’t support missing value handling.It just impute min or max from the dataset by now.

Base on the aboe two reasons, we decide to use Lightgbn as our solution.Just one step ahead of training part, we’ll convert all categorical features into class factor.

cols_all <- c("source_system_tab",
               "source_screen_name",
               "source_type",
               "city",

               "long_short"
)             

all_all[,(cols_all):= lapply(.SD, factor),.SDcols=cols_all]
all_all <- lgb.prepare2(all_all)

data_for_train_lgbm <- all_all %>%
  filter(!is.na(target)) %>%
  select(-song_id,
         -msno,
         -registration_init_time,
         -expiration_date
)
gb_train <- lgb.Dataset(data.matrix(data_for_train_lgbm %>% select(-target,-id)), 
                       label = matrix(data_for_train_lgbm$target),
                       categorical_feature=c("song_length",
                                             "genre_ids",
                                             "artist_name",
                                             "composer",
                                             "lyricist",
                                             "language",
                                             "city",
                                             "gender",
                                             "registered_via",
                                             "source_system_tab",                                             "source_screen_name",
                                             "source_type",
                                             "reg_year",
                                             "reg_month",
                                             "exp_year",
                                             "exp_month",
                                             "reg_day",
                                             "exp_day",
                                             "record_country",
                                             "record_year",
                                             "is_ft",
                                             "art_comp_same",
                                             "art_lyr_same",
                                             "art_lyr_comp_same",
                                             "long_short"))


params.lgb = list(
  objective = "binary"
  , min_data_in_leaf = 10
  , feature_fraction = 0.8
  , bagging_fraction = 0.9
  , num_leaves = 64
  , max_depth = 8
  , lambda_l2 = 10
)


lgb_cv <- lgb.cv(
  params = params.lgb
  , data = gb_train
  , boosting = "gbdt"
  , nrounds = 50
  , eval = "auc"
  , early_stopping_rounds = 10
  , nfold = 10
  , learning_rate = 0.5
  , verbose = 1
  , stratified = TRUE
  , num_threads = 4
)

Conclusion

In this notebook, we introduce through our steps of the recommendation prediction challenge.By now, we only achieve about 36% on the public leaderboard.It may owe to the absence of hyperparameter tunning and the futher model stacking because of their cost of time-consuming and we just want to show you the reader a very clear and initial progress.
